  title                = {Portfolio Selection in a Two-Regime World},
  url                  = {https://ssrn.com/abstract=2775751},
  abstract             = {Standard mean-variance analysis is based on the assumption of normal return distributions. However, a growing body of literature suggests that the market oscillates between two different regimes one with low volatility and the other with high volatility. In such a case, even if the return distributions are normal in both regimes, the overall distribution is not it is a mixture of normals. Mean-variance analysis is inappropriate in this framework, and one must either assume a specific utility function or, alternatively, employ the more general and distribution-free Second degree Stochastic Dominance (SSD) criterion. This paper develops the SSD rule for the case of Mixed Normals: the SSDMN rule. This rule is a generalization the mean-variance rule. The cost of ignoring regimes and assuming normality when the distributions are actually mixed normal can be quite substantial it is typically equivalent to an annual rate of return of 23 percent.},
