  title                = {Defining Activeness: Active Share, Risk Share and Factor Share},
  url                  = {https://ssrn.com/abstract=3084637},
  abstract             = {This paper tackles a core question of portfolio management: How 'active' is an active portfolio? To answer this question holistically, we generalise the idea of active share by keeping the same calculation methodology but substituting in different types of portfolio and benchmark 'weights'. In particular, we introduce the idea of risk share - based on asset risk weights - and factor share - based on either factor style weights or factor risk weights. Used in combination, this trio of active share, risk share and factor share provides one with a far better understanding of how an active portfolio truly differs from its benchmark.

We introduce these metrics and describe their calculations in a general multi-factor market framework. Using a set of simulated random portfolios of increasing activeness, we then investigate the relationship between active share and future active return, and between active share, tracking error and risk share. From the simulation, we find that:

(i) active share is not a predictor of future active returns,

(ii) there is a convex relationship between active share and tracking error, in line with that given mathematically in the multi-factor framework, and

(iii) portfolios of equivalent active share can have materially different risk share values, particularly evident for moderately active portfolios.

Finally, we showcase factor share by conducting an analysis on a set of South African equity funds. We find that the level of factor activeness across the funds and over time varies greatly, and that the relationship between factor active share and factor risk share calculated from the empirical data is similar to the relationship between asset active share and asset risk share calculated from the simulated data.},
